<subSubSection id="1585B48EDD1C5D544AF1FCDFFEA60D53" pageId="27" pageNumber="92" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD1C5D544AF1FCDFFF200B33" blockId="27.[130,777,854,1294]" box="[132,236,854,880]" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">FINDINGS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD1C5D544AF1FCFCFDB80C72" blockId="27.[130,777,854,1294]" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">
The 
<typeStatus id="822459A7DD1C5D544AC2FCFCFED70BD2" box="[183,283,885,911]" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD1C5D544B30FCFFFE750BD2" box="[325,441,886,911]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="27" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="grimesii">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD1C5D544B30FCFFFE750BD2" box="[325,441,886,911]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">R. grimesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears flowering branches that somewhat resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD1C5D544BB0FC1FFDFD0BF2" box="[453,561,917,943]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="27" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="floridus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD1C5D544BB0FC1FFDFD0BF2" box="[453,561,917,943]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">R. floridus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they are more curved and the angles at which their inflorescences are held are mostly less acute. In addition, the prickles on their pedicels and inflorescence rachises are finely aciculate, quite unlike the strong, hooked prickles of the 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD1C5D544BB8FB9CFDF40C73" box="[461,568,1044,1070]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="27" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="floridus">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD1C5D544BB8FB9CFDF40C73" box="[461,568,1044,1070]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">R. floridus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D20E705DD1C5D544AEEFBBDFEA60D53" blockId="27.[130,777,854,1294]" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">
Since Enslen’s specimen lacks a primocane, any clear information about plant habit, or even details about geography, we cannot determine whether it is determinate side branch from a mounding dewberry (such as 
<taxonomicName id="9A9F9C86DD1C5D5448F6FB1CFD3A0CF3" box="[643,758,1173,1198]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Rubus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="27" pageNumber="92" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="grimesii">
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD1C5D5448F6FB1CFD3A0CF3" box="[643,758,1173,1198]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">R. grimesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or from an atypical, upright 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD1C5D544BB5FB3DFD990C93" box="[448,597,1204,1230]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">Alleghenienses</emphasis>
(perhaps even a rare taxon in that section). Thus, we choose to maintain it as a 
<emphasis id="6FEB3B17DD1C5D544AC1FB7DFEA80D50" box="[180,356,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="92">nomen incertum</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
